 Climate:&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 The climate on the Costa Cálida, often considered the best in Europe, fosters a very sociable and healthy lifestyle, characterized by open-air activities, modern sports and leisure facilities, and exciting, cosmopolitan tourist towns that stand out for their top-tier services, some of them exclusive and considered truly luxurious. All of these cater to a discerning clientele seeking quality and personalized service.&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 The Costa Cálida boasts over 300 days of sunshine a year. A paradise with excellent connections to all of Europe.&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 Around:&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 If there's one place where the sun shines all year round, it's the Region of Murcia. A region with a warm climate and calm waters lapping its coast, where the crystal-clear blue of the clear, bright sky flows through every corner each day, accompanying the lives of its inhabitants.&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 The Costa Cálida continues to attract people from all over Europe, and other parts of the world, because it offers a unique quality of life in a beautiful setting on the shores of the Mar Menor, surrounded by mountains and lush vegetation.&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 In addition to the golf courses and marinas that you can enjoy all along the coast, the area also offers the opportunity to ski in the nearby Sierra Nevada, Javalambre, or Valdelinares , paradises for winter sports enthusiasts with stunning natural landscapes. The Costa Cálida offers a uniquely rich lifestyle, where the best beaches and coves of the Mediterranean combine with an interior full of mountains and villages that hold culture and historical monuments unlike any other in the world.&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 Cartagena , with its modernist buildings lining avenues that descend to the port and flank the Roman theater, is a city of contrasts. It opens onto a natural harbor provided by the bay and is surrounded by natural enclaves such as Calblanque to the east and Cabo Tiñoso to the west. The city is a transit port for large cruise ships that come to explore the region and enjoy its culture, gastronomy, and festivals, which have been declared of international tourist interest.&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 Murcia , the most welcoming capital city. Murcia experienced its golden age during the Baroque and Contemporary periods, when it was filled with palaces and churches adorned with beautiful altarpieces. The cathedral's façade, one of the most important examples of Spanish Baroque architecture, dates from this same era. Today, it is a bustling city, full of services and vibrant life, easily accessible thanks to its extensive network of highways connecting it to the various towns in the region as well as the neighboring provinces. It boasts numerous hospitals, both private and public, providing an excellent healthcare and social services network.&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 The calm waters of the Mar Menor lap the beaches of this large, unique marine lagoon, ideal for water sports and family swimming. Beyond the land barrier that separates it from the sea lies the Mediterranean, with its long beaches along La Manga del Mar Menor. There are two marinas: Lo Pagán, a harbor on the Mar Menor for gentle and sheltered sailing, and San Pedro del Pinatar, near the natural salt flats, from which to sail along the Mediterranean coast.&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
 -Quality education within your reach. Nearby are two British schools, King's College and El Limonar, where Spanish and European students learn together during their early education. Two universities, the University of Murcia and the private UCAM, complete the city's educational offerings.&amp;#13;&amp;#13;&#13;&#13;
